      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen reading a text—or even a mathematical formula—we are often tempted to assume immediately that we understand it and, consequently, that it is correct.\n\nThere are several reasons that lead us to this conclusion. However, in this introduction we will highlight one of them: the need for security, the comfort of being right, as opposed to the insecurity and fears that have accompanied us since our earliest moments of life (<htcite0>).\n\nThis fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e7e25a56-56ae-4e3c-8b00-a55a32a0f945",
                     "text": "Freud, Sigmund",
                     "page": "pp. 244, footnotes",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1913",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Security</b><br /><br />Do you feel uncomfortable when you don’t have answers?<br /><br />Do you feel uncomfortable with your mistakes?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To help us in this reflection, we will work in parallel with the sacred book of the Maya people, the *Popol-Vuh* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>), originating from Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*), and with the relationship between force and movement proposed by Isaac Newton (<htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "8fcee36c-411a-4fc8-8217-b9a07a34d3da",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, Español",
                     "page": "pp. 39",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "74bdb72d-1770-4694-8f8e-71e680f1d49c",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, English",
                     "page": "Ch. 3, pp. 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1954",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9f86c1c9-1fd7-4d22-95f6-a1b5ed13b1ee",
                     "text": "Newton, Isaac",
                     "page": "pp. 2",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1686",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_popolvuh",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Indigenous Writing\n\nIn the region known today as Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite0>), a hieroglyphic writing system was developed. These texts were inscribed on various media, such as stelae found in Copán, Honduras.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2d720f02-051c-4469-b425-7d020f2c2f9b",
                     "text": "Creamer, W.",
                     "page": "pp. 37 - 55",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1987",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanStelaA\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanStelaA', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/StelaACopan.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:30%\"/><b>Figure 4</b>: Stela A at the Copán Archaeological Museum, featuring inscriptions referencing Copán, Tikal, Calakmul, and Palenque in sequence (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1> during site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "This image displays a hieroglyphic text arranged in two columns.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In addition to the stelae, Indigenous peoples such as the Maya also wrote texts in the form of codices. Unfortunately, many of these codices were burned by Diego de Landa, who was unable to understand them (<htcite0>).\n\nThe destruction caused by Landa was not mirrored among all clergy. This context led, between <htdate0> and <htdate1>, to the compilation of ancient beliefs in what we now know as the **Popol Vuh** (<htcite1>). This event had consequences that went beyond the simple preservation of traditions. According to studies by Miguel R. Dourado, some texts do not reflect the original Mayan beliefs exactly, as they show Christian influences (<htcite2>).\n\n#### Popol Vuh\n\nThe sacred book of the Kʼicheʼ Maya expresses their understanding of cosmology and creation before the arrival of Christianity with the colonizers (<htcite3>).\n\nOriginally, the *Popol Vuh* possibly composed of a single poem. When translated into European languages, it was divided into four distinct parts that narrate the attempts to create humankind (<htcite4>).\n\nNext, we will examine a narrative found in the *Popol Vuh*. But first, another reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b7fa522f-cdc0-47e1-b0a5-049a2bb463db",
                     "text": "Timmer, David E.",
                     "page": "pp. 479-480",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85cb27e2-5854-456d-9a0a-2123fa5c0975",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Popol Vuh",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0fe64269-28a5-4f86-a0a2-aaf78619183f",
                     "text": "Dourado, Miguel R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85cb27e2-5854-456d-9a0a-2123fa5c0975",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Popol Vuh",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85cb27e2-5854-456d-9a0a-2123fa5c0975",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Popol Vuh",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1554",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1558",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Contradictions</b><br /><br />When you encounter an idea that contradicts your own, do you immediately classify it as wrong?<br /><br />Or do you stop, think, and study that opposing idea?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Inorganic Matter and Life\n\nToday, when we speak of living beings, we often limit ourselves to plants and animals—but it has not always been this way. Many ancient peoples believed in “lightning stones,” to which they attributed great importance in relation to life (<htcite0>).\n\nWhen reading the *Popol Vuh*, we also find that, according to the narratives, in ancient times “all spoke: grinding stones” (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nAt first glance, this relationship between stones, texts, and beliefs might lead us to conclude that such ideas are mistaken. On the other hand, it may also show that certain perspectives only consider two extremes, leading to polarized thinking (<htcite3>)",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56169de2-3737-4ca2-a857-ffc29bf9fb35",
                     "text": "Garcia Castro, Juan Antonio",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1988",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "8fcee36c-411a-4fc8-8217-b9a07a34d3da",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, Espanhol",
                     "page": "pp. 39",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "74bdb72d-1770-4694-8f8e-71e680f1d49c",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, English",
                     "page": "Ch. 3, pp. 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1954",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3c81aa4a-3030-4767-861a-25f13272776f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Sempre presente",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Limits 1</b><br /><br />What if the <i>Popol Vuh</i> was not written literally, but symbolically—as an abstraction?<br ></br>Before this reflection, had the possibility that the texts might not be literal ever crossed your mind?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Abstraction and Facts\n\nIn the 19th century, according to the Gregorian calendar, Charles S. Peirce proposed that thought should not be considered exclusive to human beings. He even extended this idea to crystals (<htcite0>).\n\nAstronomical measurements made with telescopes show that the universe is expanding (<htcite1>), which indicates that in the past it was contracted—as explained in Chapter 4 of the *Literature* section and also in the *Atlas* of *History Tracers* (<htcite2>; <htcite3>). These data suggest that there is a connection among all elements present in nature.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f2efe0a4-6e8b-4ec1-8c7e-ebfd28ffa67f",
                     "text": "Santaella, Lucia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1af85131-52aa-49ee-8f9b-2409eb806900",
                     "text": "Hubble, Edwin",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1929",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2806b294-0d2a-4ca2-8008-b2b82791427a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Undestandig Texts",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f140d8d6-80cc-4d82-b9f7-c3ba06bf2ed3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Atlas",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/ESA/Planck_history_of_Universe.jpg\" id=\"imgESA2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgESA2', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 2</b>: Planck history of Universe. ©ESA – C. Carreau (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9'); return false;\"><i>ESA</i></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Context\n\nDifferent Mesoamerican peoples used grinding stones (Figure 3) to prepare their food—that is, the stone was directly connected to their daily life. Likewise, stones also played an important role in the lives of various ancient cultures (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56169de2-3737-4ca2-a857-ffc29bf9fb35",
                     "text": "Garcia Castro, Juan Antonio",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1988",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"metate3\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/MetateTeotihuacan.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('metate3', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 3</b>: Metate from Mexico. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the Achaeological Site of Teotihuacan, México.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "In this metate, we see two front supports (“legs”) and a rear support located at the center of a curved rectangular piece. On the top, there is a roller used to grind corn.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_newton",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Scientific Texts\n\nIt is not only in literary works that people attempt to understand content in a literal and complete way; this also occurs in scientific texts, which often leads to interpretation errors. To illustrate this issue, let us analyze the relationship between force and motion, discovered by Isaac Newton (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9f86c1c9-1fd7-4d22-95f6-a1b5ed13b1ee",
                     "text": "Newton, Isaac",
                     "page": "pp. 2",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1686",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>An impressed force is an action exerted upon a body in order to change its state, whether from rest or from uniform motion forward in a straight line.</i></li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 4: Limits 2</b><br /><br />If an applied force changes the state of motion, this could imply that by increasing the force, the body would move increasingly faster.<br /><br />But does this actually occur in nature?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Atoms\n\nIsaac Newton’s model (<htcite0>) was proposed at a time when human knowledge was focused on the visible world.\n\nWhen models such as Rutherford’s atomic model emerged (see Graph 1) (<htcite1>), researchers sought to apply known principles to verify their validity. However, as these models failed to fully explain experimental results, the need arose to develop new theories.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9f86c1c9-1fd7-4d22-95f6-a1b5ed13b1ee",
                     "text": "Newton, Isaac",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1686",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2fd2e872-c5d8-4f1b-91dc-97df40597c4e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Evolution of Knowledge: The Atom",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"15\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"15\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"134\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"134\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"134\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"114\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"114\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"114\" font-size=\"1em\">A</text> <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"64\" x2=\"115\" y2=\"64\" stroke=\"black\" />  <line x1=\"115\" y1=\"64\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"35\" y=\"50\" font-size=\"1em\">B</text>  <line x1=\"0\" y1=\"36\" x2=\"155\" y2=\"36\" stroke=\"black\" /> <line x1=\"155\" y1=\"36\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"50\" stroke=\"black\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"270\" y=\"50\" font-size=\"1em\">C</text> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"75\" r=\"30\"></circle> <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"27\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  <circle cx=\"75\" cy=\"75\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"73\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text> <text x=\"120\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <text x=\"140\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <text x=\"140\" y=\"100\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text>  <text x=\"160\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">+</text> <circle cx=\"205\" cy=\"75\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"202\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  <circle cx=\"145\" cy=\"125\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FF9999\"></circle><text x=\"143\" y=\"127\" font-size=\"1em\">-</text>  </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Representation of Rutherford model.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "Representation of Rutherford's atom, which features a large positive nucleus and small, negatively charged electrons around it.",
               "format": "html",
