               "text": "#### The Aether\n\nThe explanation that increasing force automatically leads to a proportional increase in velocity was not the only model inconsistent with experimental data.\n\nAt the beginning of the twentieth century, according to the Gregorian calendar, the idea that the universe was filled with an “aether” still persisted. This concept made it difficult to interpret Lorentz’s work on light, which agreed with Newtonian mechanics only at low velocities (<htcite0>).\n\n#### The Solution\n\nBoth problems were solved by Albert Einstein in <htdate0>, when he proposed that Lorentz’s transformations were not limited to light alone. Furthermore, he demonstrated that velocity measurements depend on the observer.\n\nHis theory eliminated the need for the ether hypothesis and introduced the idea of a universal maximum speed (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\n#### The Context\n\nNewton’s proposals were formulated based on an inertial frame of reference, derived from macroscopic studies. In contrast, when dealing with light and extremely small matter such as atoms, we enter a different scenario, even though both involve material phenomena.\n\nThe models of Einstein and Lorentz, as well as Newton’s, each accurately explain phenomena within their respective contexts. Moreover, it is possible to establish a relationship between them by considering the magnitude of velocity involved.",
